# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mesa-graphics-stack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The **Direct Rendering Manager** (**DRM**) is a subsystem of the Linux kernel responsible for interfacing with GPUs of modern video cards.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] DRM exposes an API that user-space programs can use to send commands and data to the GPU and perform operations such as configuring the mode setting of the display.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] DRM was first developed as the kernel-space component of the X Server Direct Rendering Infrastructure, but since then it has been used by other graphic stack alternatives such as Wayland and standalone applications and libraries such as SDL2 and Kodi.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] User-space programs can use the DRM API to command the GPU to do hardware-accelerated 3D rendering and video decoding, as well as GPGPU computing.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The Linux kernel already had an API called fbdev, used to manage the framebuffer of a graphics adapter, but it couldn't be used to handle the needs of modern 3D-accelerated GPU-based video hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] These devices usually require setting and managing a command queue in their own memory to dispatch commands to the GPU and also require management of buffers and free space within that memory.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Initially, user-space programs (such as the X Server) directly managed these resources, but they usually acted as if they were the only ones with access to them.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] When two or more programs tried to control the same hardware at the same time, and set its resources each one in its own way, most times they ended catastrophically.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] DRM allows multiple programs concurrent access to the 3D video card, avoiding collisions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The Direct Rendering Manager was created to allow multiple programs to use video hardware resources cooperatively.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The DRM gets exclusive access to the GPU and is responsible for initializing and maintaining the command queue, memory, and any other hardware resource.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Programs wishing to use the GPU send requests to DRM, which acts as an arbitrator and takes care to avoid possible conflicts.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The scope of DRM has been expanded over the years to cover more functionality previously handled by user-space programs, such as framebuffer managing and mode setting, memory-sharing objects and memory synchronization.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Some of these expansions were given specific names, such as Graphics Execution Manager (GEM) or kernel mode-setting (KMS), and the terminology prevails when the functionality they provide is specifically alluded.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] But they are really parts of the whole kernel DRM subsystem.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The trend to include two GPUs in a computer—a discrete GPU and an integrated one—led to new problems such as GPU switching that also needed to be solved at the DRM layer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In order to match the Nvidia Optimus technology, DRM was provided with GPU offloading abilities, called PRIME.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The Direct Rendering Manager resides in kernel space, so user-space programs must use kernel system calls to request its services.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] However, DRM doesn't define its own customized system calls.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Instead, it follows the Unix principle of "everything is a file" to expose the GPUs through the filesystem name space, using device files under the `/dev` hierarchy.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Each GPU detected by DRM is referred to as a *DRM device*, and a device file `/dev/dri/card*X*` (where *X* is a sequential number) is created to interface with it.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] User-space programs that want to talk to the GPU must open this file and use ioctl calls to communicate with DRM.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Different ioctls correspond to different functions of the DRM API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] A library called *libdrm* was created to facilitate the interface of user-space programs with the DRM subsystem.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This library is merely a wrapper that provides a function written in C for every ioctl of the DRM API, as well as constants, structures and other helper elements.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The use of libdrm not only avoids exposing the kernel interface directly to applications, but presents the usual advantages of reusing and sharing code between programs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] DRM consists of two parts: a generic "DRM core" and a specific one ("DRM driver") for each type of supported hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] DRM core provides the basic framework where different DRM drivers can register and also provides to user space a minimal set of ioctls with common, hardware-independent functionality.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] When a specific DRM driver provides an enhanced API, user-space libdrm is also extended by an extra library libdrm-*driver* that can be used by user space to interface with the additional ioctls.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The DRM core exports several interfaces to user-space applications, generally intended to be used through corresponding `libdrm` wrapper functions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In addition, drivers export device-specific interfaces for use by user-space drivers and device-aware applications through ioctls and sysfs files.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] External interfaces include: memory mapping, context management, DMA operations, AGP management, vblank control, fence management, memory management, and output management.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] There are several operations (ioctls) in the DRM API that either for security purposes or for concurrency issues must be restricted to be used by a single user-space process per device.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] To implement this restriction, DRM limits such ioctls to be only invoked by the process considered the "master" of a DRM device, usually called *DRM-Master*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Only one of all processes that have the device node `/dev/dri/card*X*` opened will have its file handle marked as master, specifically the first calling the SET_MASTER ioctl.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Any attempt to use one of these restricted ioctls without being the DRM-Master will return an error.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] A process can also give up its master role—and let another process acquire it—by calling the DROP_MASTER ioctl.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The X Server—or any other display server—is commonly the process that acquires the DRM-Master status in every DRM device it manages, usually when it opens the corresponding device node during its startup, and keeps these privileges for the entire graphical session until it finishes or dies.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For the remaining user-space processes there is another way to gain the privilege to invoke some restricted operations on the DRM device called *DRM-Auth*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] It is basically a method of authentication against the DRM device, in order to prove to it that the process has the DRM-Master's approval to get such privileges.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Due to the increasing size of video memory and the growing complexity of graphics APIs such as OpenGL, the strategy of reinitializing the graphics card state at each context switch was too expensive, performance-wise.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Also, modern Linux desktops needed an optimal way to share off-screen buffers with the compositing manager.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] These requirements led to the development of new methods to manage graphics buffers inside the kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The *Graphics Execution Manager* (GEM) emerged as one of these methods.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM provides an API with explicit memory management primitives.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Through GEM, a user-space program can create, handle and destroy memory objects living in the GPU video memory.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] These objects, called "GEM objects", are persistent from the user-space program's perspective and don't need to be reloaded every time the program regains control of the GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] When a user-space program needs a chunk of video memory (to store a framebuffer, texture or any other data required by the GPU), it requests the allocation to the DRM driver using the GEM API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The DRM driver keeps track of the used video memory and is able to comply with the request if there is free memory available, returning a "handle" to user space to further refer the allocated memory in coming operations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM API also provides operations to populate the buffer and to release it when it is not needed anymore.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Memory from unreleased GEM handles gets recovered when the user-space process closes the DRM device file descriptor—intentionally or because it terminates.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM also allows two or more user-space processes using the same DRM device (hence the same DRM driver) to share a GEM object.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM handles are local 32-bit integers unique to a process but repeatable in other processes, therefore not suitable for sharing.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] What is needed is a global namespace, and GEM provides one through the use of global handles called *GEM names*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] A GEM name refers to one, and only one, GEM object created within the same DRM device by the same DRM driver, by using a unique 32-bit integer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM provides an operation *flink* to obtain a GEM name from a GEM handle.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The process can then pass this GEM name (32-bit integer) to another process using any IPC mechanism available.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The GEM name can be used by the recipient process to obtain a local GEM handle pointing to the original GEM object.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Unfortunately, the use of GEM names to share buffers is not secure.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] A malicious third-party process accessing the same DRM device could try to guess the GEM name of a buffer shared by two other processes, simply by probing 32-bit integers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Once a GEM name is found, its contents can be accessed and modified, violating the confidentiality and integrity of the information of the buffer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This drawback was overcome later by the introduction of DMA-BUF support into DRM, as DMA-BUF represents buffers in userspace as file descriptors, which may be shared securely.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Another important task for any video-memory management system besides managing the video-memory space is handling the memory synchronization between the GPU and the CPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Current memory architectures are very complex and usually involve various levels of caches for the system memory and sometimes for the video memory too.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Therefore, video-memory managers should also handle the cache coherence to ensure the data shared between CPU and GPU is consistent.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This means that often video-memory management internals are highly dependent on hardware details of the GPU and memory architecture, and thus driver-specific.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM was initially developed by Intel engineers to provide a video-memory manager for its i915 driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The Intel GMA 9xx family are integrated GPUs with a Uniform Memory Architecture (UMA), where the GPU and CPU share the physical memory, and there is not a dedicated VRAM.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM defines "memory domains" for memory synchronization, and while these memory domains are GPU-independent, they are specifically designed with an UMA memory architecture in mind, making them less suitable for other memory architectures like those with a separate VRAM.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For this reason, other DRM drivers have decided to expose to user-space programs the GEM API, but internally they implemented a different memory manager better suited for their particular hardware and memory architecture.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The GEM API also provides ioctls for control of the execution flow (command buffers), but they are Intel-specific, to be used with Intel i915 and later GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] No other DRM driver has attempted to implement any part of the GEM API beyond the memory-management specific ioctls.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The main concept of TTM are the "buffer objects", regions of video memory that at some point must be addressable by the GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] When a user-space graphics application wants access to a certain buffer object (usually to fill it with content), TTM may require relocating it to a type of memory addressable by the CPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Further relocations—or GART mapping operations—could happen when the GPU needs access to a buffer object but it isn't in the GPU's address space yet.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Each of these relocation operations must handle any related data and cache-coherency issues.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Another important TTM concept is *fences*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Fences are essentially a mechanism to manage concurrency between the CPU and the GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] A fence tracks when a buffer object is no longer used by the GPU, generally to notify any user-space process with access to it.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Some DRM developers thought that it wouldn't fit well with any specific driver, especially the API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] When GEM emerged as a simpler memory manager, its API was preferred over the TTM one.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] But some driver developers considered that the approach taken by TTM was more suitable for discrete video cards with dedicated video memory and IOMMUs, so they decided to use TTM internally, while exposing their buffer objects as GEM objects and thus supporting the GEM API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Examples of current drivers using TTM as an internal memory manager but providing a GEM API are the radeon driver for AMD video cards and the nouveau driver for NVIDIA video cards.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The *DMA Buffer Sharing API* (often abbreviated as DMA-BUF) is a Linux kernel internal API designed to provide a generic mechanism to share DMA buffers across multiple devices, possibly managed by different types of device drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For example, a Video4Linux device and a graphics adapter device could share buffers through DMA-BUF to achieve zero-copy of the data of a video stream produced by the first and consumed by the latter.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Any Linux device driver can implement this API as exporter, as user (consumer) or both.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This feature was exploited for the first time in DRM to implement PRIME, a solution for GPU offloading that uses DMA-BUF to share the resulting framebuffers between the DRM drivers of the discrete and the integrated GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] An important feature of DMA-BUF is that a shared buffer is presented to user space as a file descriptor.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For the development of PRIME two new ioctls were added to the DRM API, one to convert a local GEM handle to a DMA-BUF file descriptor and another for the exact opposite operation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] These two new ioctls were later reused as a way to fix the inherent unsafety of GEM buffer sharing.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Unlike GEM names, file descriptors can not be guessed (they are not a global namespace), and Unix operating systems provide a safe way to pass them through a Unix domain socket using the SCM_RIGHTS semantics.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] A process that wants to share a GEM object with another process can convert its local GEM handle to a DMA-BUF file descriptor and pass it to the recipient, which in turn can get its own GEM handle from the received file descriptor.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This method is used by DRI3 to share buffers between the client and the X Server and also by Wayland.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In order to work properly, a video card or graphics adapter must set a *mode*—a combination of screen resolution, color depth and refresh rate—that is within the range of values supported by itself and the attached display screen.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This operation is called mode-setting, and it usually requires raw access to the graphics hardware—i.e. the ability to write to certain registers of the video card display controller.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] A mode-setting operation must be performed before starting to use the framebuffer, and also when the mode is required to change by an application or the user.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In the early days, user-space programs that wanted to use the graphical framebuffer were also responsible for providing the mode-setting operations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Thus, they needed to run with privileged access to the video hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In Unix-type operating systems, the X Server was the most prominent example.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Its mode-setting implementation lived in the DDX driver for each specific type of video card.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This approach, later referred to as *User space Mode-Setting* or UMS, poses several issues.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] It not only breaks the isolation that operating systems should provide between programs and hardware, raising both stability and security concerns, but also could leave the graphics hardware in an inconsistent state if two or more user space programs try to do the mode-setting at the same time.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] To avoid these conflicts, the X Server became in practice the only user space program that performed mode-setting operations; the remainder user space programs relied on the X Server to set the appropriate mode and to handle any other operation involving mode-setting.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Initially the mode-setting was performed exclusively during the X Server startup process, but later the X Server gained the ability to do it while running.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The XFree86-VidModeExtension extension was introduced in XFree86 3.1.2 to let any X client request modeline (resolution) changes to the X Server.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] VidMode extension was later superseded by the more generic XRandR extension.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] However, this was not the only code doing mode-setting in a Linux system.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] During the system booting process, the Linux kernel must set a minimal text mode for the virtual console (based on the standard modes defined by VESA BIOS extensions).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Also the Linux kernel framebuffer driver contained mode-setting code to configure framebuffer devices.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] To avoid mode-setting conflicts, the XFree86 Server—and later the X.Org Server—handled the case when the user switched from the graphical environment to a text virtual console by saving its mode-setting state, and restoring it when the user switched back to X.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This process caused an annoying flicker in the transition, and also can fail, leading to a corrupted or unusable output display.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] To address these problems, the mode-setting code was moved to a single place inside the kernel, specifically to the existing DRM module.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Then, every process—including the X Server—should be able to command the kernel to perform mode-setting operations, and the kernel would ensure that concurrent operations don't result in an inconsistent state.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The new kernel API and code added to the DRM module to perform these mode-setting operations was called *Kernel Mode-Setting* (KMS).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Kernel Mode-Setting provides several benefits.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The most immediate is of course the removal of duplicate mode-setting code, from both the kernel (Linux console, fbdev) and user space (X Server DDX drivers).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] KMS also makes it easier to write alternative graphics systems, which now don't need to implement their own mode-setting code.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] By providing centralized mode management, KMS solves the flickering issues while changing between console and X, and also between different instances of X (fast user switching).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Since it is available in the kernel, it can also be used at the beginning of the boot process, saving flickering due to mode changes in these early stages.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The fact that KMS is part of the kernel allows it to use resources only available at kernel space such as interrupts.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For example, the mode recovery after a suspend/resume process simplifies a lot by being managed by the kernel itself, and incidentally improves security (no more user space tools requiring root permissions).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The kernel also allows the hotplug of new display devices easily, solving a longstanding problem.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Mode-setting is also closely related to memory management—since framebuffers are basically memory buffers—so a tight integration with the graphics memory manager is highly recommended.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] That's the main reason why the kernel mode-setting code was incorporated into DRM and not as a separate subsystem.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] To avoid breaking backwards compatibility of the DRM API, Kernel Mode-Setting is provided as an additional *driver feature* of certain DRM drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Any DRM driver can choose to provide the DRIVER_MODESET flag when it registers with the DRM core to indicate that supports the KMS API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Those drivers that implement Kernel Mode-Setting are often called *KMS drivers* as a way to differentiate them from the legacy—without KMS—DRM drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] KMS has been adopted to such an extent that certain drivers which lack 3D acceleration (or for which the hardware vendor doesn't want to expose or implement it) nevertheless implement the KMS API without the rest of the DRM API, allowing display servers (like Wayland) to run with ease.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] KMS models and manages the output devices as a series of abstract hardware blocks commonly found on the display output pipeline of a display controller.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In recent years there has been an ongoing effort to bring atomicity to some regular operations pertaining the KMS API, specifically to the mode setting and page flipping operations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This enhanced KMS API is what is called *Atomic Display* (formerly known as *atomic mode-setting* and *atomic* or *nuclear pageflip*).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Atomic mode-setting allows one to know beforehand if certain specific mode configuration is appropriate, by providing mode testing capabilities.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] When an atomic mode is tested and its validity confirmed, it can be applied with a single indivisible (atomic) commit operation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Both test and commit operations are provided by the same new ioctl with different flags.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The new atomic API is built upon the old KMS API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] It uses the same model and objects (CRTCs, encoders, connectors, planes, ...), but with an increasing number of object properties that can be modified.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The atomic procedure is based on changing the relevant properties to build the state that we want to test or commit.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The properties we want to modify depend on whether we want to do a mode-setting (mostly CRTCs, encoders and connectors properties) or page flipping (usually planes properties).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The ioctl is the same for both cases, the difference being the list of properties passed with each one.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In the original DRM API, the DRM device `/dev/dri/card*X*` is used for both privileged (modesetting, other display control) and non-privileged (rendering, GPGPU compute) operations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For security reasons, opening the associated DRM device file requires special privileges "equivalent to root-privileges".
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This leads to an architecture where only some reliable user space programs (the X server, a graphical compositor, ...) have full access to the DRM API, including the privileged parts like the modeset API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Other user space applications that want to render or make GPGPU computations should be granted by the owner of the DRM device ("DRM Master") through the use of a special authentication interface.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Then the authenticated applications can render or make computations using a restricted version of the DRM API without privileged operations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The "render nodes" concept tries to solve these scenarios by splitting the DRM user space API into two interfaces – one privileged and one non-privileged – and using separate device files (or "nodes") for each one.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For every GPU found, its corresponding DRM driver—if it supports the render nodes feature—creates a device file `/dev/dri/renderD*X*`, called the *render node*, in addition to the primary node `/dev/dri/card*X*`.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Display servers, compositors and any other program that requires the modeset API or any other privileged operation must open the standard primary node that grants access to the full DRM API and use it as usual.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Render nodes explicitly disallow the GEM *flink* operation to prevent buffer sharing using insecure GEM global names; only PRIME (DMA-BUF) file descriptors can be used to share buffers with another client, including the graphics server.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The Linux DRM subsystem includes free and open-source drivers to support hardware from the 3 main manufacturers of GPUs for desktop computers (AMD, NVIDIA and Intel), as well as from a growing number of mobile GPU and System on a chip (SoC) integrators.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The quality of each driver varies highly, depending on the degree of cooperation by the manufacturer and other matters.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] There is also a number of drivers for old, obsolete hardware detailed in the next table for historical purposes.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The Direct Rendering Manager is developed within the Linux kernel, and its source code resides in the `/drivers/gpu/drm` directory of the Linux source code.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The subsystem maintainer is Dave Airlie, with other maintainers taking care of specific drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] As usual in the Linux kernel development, DRM submaintainers and contributors send their patches with new features and bug fixes to the main DRM maintainer which integrates them into its own Linux repository.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The DRM maintainer in turn submits all of these patches that are ready to be mainlined to Linus Torvalds whenever a new Linux version is going to be released.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Torvalds, as top maintainer of the whole kernel, holds the last word on whether a patch is suitable or not for inclusion in the kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] For historical reasons, the source code of the libdrm library is maintained under the umbrella of the Mesa project.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In 1999, while developing DRI for XFree86, Precision Insight created the first version of DRM for the 3dfx video cards, as a Linux kernel patch included within the Mesa source code.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Later that year, the DRM code was mainlined in Linux kernel 2.3.18 under the `/drivers/char/drm/` directory for character devices.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] During the following years the number of supported video cards grew.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The split of DRM into two components, DRM core and DRM driver, called *DRM core/personality split* was done during the second half of 2004, and merged into kernel version 2.6.11.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This split allowed multiple DRM drivers for multiple devices to work simultaneously, opening the way to multi-GPU support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Such code had to be executed using x86 real mode, which prevented it from being invoked by a kernel running in protected mode.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The situation changed when Luc Verhaegen and other developers found a way to do the mode-setting natively instead of BIOS-based, showing that it was possible to do it using normal kernel code and laying the groundwork for what would become *Kernel Mode Setting*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In May 2007 Jesse Barnes (Intel) published the first proposal for a *drm-modesetting* API and a working native implementation of mode-setting for Intel GPUs within the i915 DRM driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In December 2007 Jerome Glisse started to add the native mode-setting code for ATI cards to the radeon DRM driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Work on both the API and drivers continued during 2008, but got delayed by the necessity of a memory manager also in kernel space to handle the framebuffers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In October 2008 the Linux kernel 2.6.27 brought a major source code reorganization, prior to some significant upcoming changes.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The DRM source code tree was moved to its own source directory `/drivers/gpu/drm/` and the different drivers were moved into their own subdirectories.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Headers were also moved into a new `/include/drm` directory.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The increasing complexity of video memory management led to several approaches to solving this issue.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The first attempt was the *Translation Table Maps* (TTM) memory manager, developed by Thomas Hellstrom (Tungsten Graphics) in collaboration with Emma Anholt (Intel) and Dave Airlie (Red Hat).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] TTM was proposed for inclusion into mainline kernel 2.6.25 in November 2007, and again in May 2008, but was ditched in favor of a new approach called *Graphics Execution Manager* (GEM).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM was first developed by Keith Packard and Emma Anholt from Intel as a simpler solution for memory management for their i915 driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] GEM was well received and merged into the Linux kernel version 2.6.28 released in December 2008.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Meanwhile, TTM had to wait until September 2009 to be finally merged into Linux 2.6.31 as a requirement of the new Radeon KMS DRM driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] With memory management in place to handle buffer objects, DRM developers could finally add to the kernel the already finished API and code to do mode setting.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This expanded API is what is called *Kernel Mode-setting* (KMS) and the drivers which implement it are often referred to as *KMS drivers*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In March 2009, KMS was merged into the Linux kernel version 2.6.29, along with KMS support for the i915 driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The KMS API has been exposed to user space programs since libdrm 2.4.3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The userspace X.Org DDX driver for Intel graphics cards was also the first to use the new GEM and KMS APIs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] KMS support for the radeon DRM driver was added to Linux 2.6.31 release of September 2009.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The new radeon KMS driver used the TTM memory manager but exposed GEM-compatible interfaces and ioctls instead of TTM ones.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Since 2006 the nouveau project had been developing a free software DRM driver for NVIDIA GPUs outside of the official Linux kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In 2010 the nouveau source code was merged into Linux 2.6.33 as an experimental driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] At the time of merging, the driver had been already converted to KMS, and behind the GEM API it used TTM as its memory manager.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The new KMS API—including the GEM API—was a big milestone in the development of DRM, but it didn't stop the API from being enhanced in the following years.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] KMS gained support for page flips in conjunction with asynchronous VBLANK notifications in Linux 2.6.33—only for the i915 driver, radeon and nouveau added it later during Linux 2.6.38 release.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The new page flip interface was added to libdrm 2.4.17.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In early 2011, during the Linux 2.6.39 release cycle, the so-called *dumb buffers*—a hardware-independent non-accelerated way to handle simple buffers suitable for use as framebuffers—were added to the KMS API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The goal was to reduce the complexity of applications such as Plymouth that don't need to use special accelerated operations provided by driver-specific ioctls.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The feature was exposed by libdrm from version 2.4.25 onwards.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Later that year it also gained a new main type of objects, called *planes*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Planes were developed to represent hardware overlays supported by the scanout engine.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Plane support was merged into Linux 3.3. and libdrm 2.4.30.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Another concept added to the API—during Linux 3.5 and libdrm 2.4.36 releases—were *generic object properties*, a method to add generic values to any KMS object.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Properties are specially useful to set special behaviour or features to objects such as CRTCs and planes.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] An early proof of concept to provide GPU offloading between DRM drivers was developed by Dave Airlie in 2010.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Since Airlie was trying to mimic the NVIDIA Optimus technology, he decided to name it "PRIME".
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Airlie resumed his work on PRIME in late 2011, but based on the new DMA-BUF buffer sharing mechanism introduced by Linux kernel 3.3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The basic DMA-BUF PRIME infrastructure was finished in March 2012 and merged into the Linux 3.4 release, as well as into libdrm 2.4.34.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Later during the Linux 3.5 release, several DRM drivers implemented PRIME support, including i915 for Intel cards, radeon for AMD cards and nouveau for NVIDIA cards.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In recent years, the DRM API has incrementally expanded with new and improved features.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In 2013, as part of GSoC, David Herrmann developed the multiple *render nodes* feature.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] His code was added to the Linux kernel version 3.12 as an experimental feature supported by i915, radeon and nouveau drivers, and enabled by default since Linux 3.17.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In 2014 Matt Roper (Intel) developed the *universal planes* (or *unified planes*) concept by which framebuffers (*primary planes*), overlays (*secondary planes*) and cursors (*cursor planes*) are all treated as a single type of object with an unified API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Universal planes support provides a more consistent DRM API with fewer, more generic ioctls.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In order to maintain the API backwards compatible, the feature is exposed by DRM core as an additional capability that a DRM driver can provide.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Universal plane support debuted in Linux 3.15 and libdrm 2.4.55.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Several drivers, such as the Intel i915, have already implemented it.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The most recent DRM API enhancement is the *atomic mode-setting* API, which brings atomicity to the mode-setting and page flipping operations on a DRM device.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The idea of an atomic API for mode-setting was first proposed in early 2012.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Ville Syrjälä (Intel) took over the task of designing and implementing such atomic API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Based on his work, Rob Clark (Texas Instruments) took a similar approach aiming to implement atomic page flips.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Later in 2013 both proposed features were reunited in a single one using a single ioctl for both tasks.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Since it was a requirement, the feature had to wait for the support of universal planes to be merged in mid-2014.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] During the second half of 2014 the atomic code was greatly enhanced by Daniel Vetter (Intel) and other DRM developers in order to facilitate the transition for the existing KMS drivers to the new atomic framework.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] All of this work was finally merged into Linux 3.19 and Linux 4.0 releases, and enabled by default since Linux 4.2. libdrm exposed the new atomic API since version 2.4.62.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Multiple drivers have already been converted to the new atomic API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] By 2018 ten new DRM drivers based on this new atomic model had been added to the Linux kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] The Direct Rendering Manager kernel subsystem was initially developed to be used with the new Direct Rendering Infrastructure of the XFree86 4.0 display server, later inherited by its successor, the X.Org Server.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Therefore, the main users of DRM were DRI clients that link to the hardware-accelerated OpenGL implementation that lives in the Mesa 3D library, as well as the X Server itself.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] Nowadays DRM is also used by several Wayland compositors, including Weston reference compositor. kmscon is a virtual console implementation that runs in user space using DRM KMS facilities.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] In 2015, version 358.09 (beta) of the proprietary Nvidia GeForce driver received support for the DRM mode-setting interface implemented as a new kernel blob called `nvidia-modeset.ko`.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/direct-rendering-manager] This new driver component works in conjunction with the `nvidia.ko` kernel module to program the display engine (i.e. display controller) of the GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] A **free and open-source graphics device driver** is a software stack which controls computer-graphics hardware and supports graphics-rendering application programming interfaces (APIs) and is released under a free and open-source software license.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Graphics device drivers are written for specific hardware to work within a specific operating system kernel and to support a range of APIs used by applications to access the graphics hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] They may also control output to the display if the display driver is part of the graphics hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Most free and open-source graphics device drivers are developed by the Mesa project.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The driver is made up of a compiler, a rendering API, and software which manages access to the graphics hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Drivers without freely (and legally) available source code are commonly known as *binary drivers*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Binary drivers used in the context of operating systems that are prone to ongoing development and change (such as Linux) create problems for end users and package maintainers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] These problems, which affect system stability, security and performance, are the main reason for the independent development of free and open-source drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] When no technical documentation is available, an understanding of the underlying hardware is often gained by clean-room reverse engineering.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Based on this understanding, device drivers may be written and legally published under any software license.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In rare cases, a manufacturer's driver source code is available on the Internet without a free license.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] This means that the code can be studied and altered for personal use, but the altered (and usually the original) source code cannot be freely distributed.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Solutions to bugs in the driver cannot be easily shared in the form of modified versions of the driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Therefore, the utility of such drivers is significantly reduced in comparison to free and open-source drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] There are objections to binary-only drivers based on copyright, security, reliability and development concerns.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] It is speculated that the bug has existed since 2004; Nvidia has denied this, asserting that the issue was only communicated to them in July 2006 and the 2004 bug was a bug in X.Org (not in Nvidia's driver).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Features like kernel mode-setting cannot be added to binary drivers by anyone but the vendors, which prevents their inclusion if the vendor lacks capacity or interest.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In the Linux kernel development community, Linus Torvalds has made strong statements on the issue of binary-only modules: "I *refuse* to even consider tying my hands over some binary-only module ...
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] I want people to know that when they use binary-only modules, it's *their* problem".
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In the case of binary drivers, there are objections due to free software philosophy, software quality and security concerns.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Linux kernel has never maintained a stable in-kernel application binary interface.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] There are also concerns that proprietary drivers may contain backdoors, like the one found in Samsung Galaxy-series modem drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] When applications such as a 3D game engine or a 3D computer graphics software shunt calculations from the CPU to the GPU, they usually use a special-purpose API like OpenGL or Direct3D and do not address the hardware directly.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Because all translation (from API calls to GPU opcodes) is done by the device driver, it contains specialized knowledge and is an object of optimization.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Due to the history of the rigidity of proprietary driver development there has been a recent surge in the number of community-backed device drivers for desktop and mobile GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Free and Open Hardware organizations like FOSSi, LowRISC, and others, would also benefit from the development of an open graphical hardware standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] This would then provide computer manufacturers, hobbyists, and the like with a complete, royalty-free platform with which to develop computing hardware and related devices.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The desktop computer market was long dominated by PC hardware using the x86/x86-64 instruction set and GPUs available for the PC.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] With three major competitors (Nvidia, AMD and Intel).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The main competing factor was the price of hardware and raw performance in 3D computer games, which is greatly affected by the efficient translation of API calls into GPU opcodes.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The display driver and the video decoder are inherent parts of the graphics card: hardware designed to assist in the calculations necessary for the decoding of video streams.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] As the market for PC hardware has dwindled, it seems unlikely that new competitors will enter this market and it is unclear how much more knowledge one company could gain by seeing the source code of other companies' drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The mobile sector presents a different situation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The development goal is not only raw 3D performance, but system integration, power consumption and 2D capabilities.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] There is also an approach which abandons the traditional method (Vsync) of updating the display and makes better use of sample and hold technology to lower power consumption.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] During the second quarter of 2013 79.3% of smartphones sold worldwide were running a version of Android, and the Linux kernel dominates smartphones.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Hardware developers have an incentive to deliver Linux drivers for their hardware but, due to competition, no incentive to make these drivers free and open-source.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Additional problems are the Android-specific augmentations to the Linux kernel which have not been accepted in mainline, such as the Atomic Display Framework (ADF).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] ADF is a feature of 3.10 AOSP kernels which provides a dma-buf-centric framework between Android's hwcomposer HAL and the kernel driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] ADF significantly overlaps with the DRM-KMS framework.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] ADF has not been accepted into mainline, but a different set of solutions addressing the same problems (known as atomic mode setting) is under development.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Projects such as libhybris harness Android device drivers to run on Linux platforms other than Android.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Free and open-source drivers are primarily developed on and for Linux by Linux kernel developers, third-party programming enthusiasts and employees of companies such as Advanced Micro Devices.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] This component is hardware-specific; it is executed on the CPU and translates OpenGL commands, for example, into machine code for the GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Because the device driver is split, marshalling is possible.
