[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The user-mode remains closed source and is published with prebuilt binaries in the driver and the CUDA toolkit." The open source driver has since been upgraded to production status and is now officially recommended for the RTX 20 series and later GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Blackwell (RTX 50 generation) and later NVIDIA GPU architectures are only supported by the open driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Intel has a history of producing (or commissioning) open-source drivers for its graphics chips, with the exception of their PowerVR-based chips.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Their 2D X.Org driver is called xf86-video-intel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The kernel mode-setting driver in the Linux kernel does not use the video BIOS for switching video modes; since some BIOSes have a limited range of modes, this provides more reliable access to those supported by Intel video adapters.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The company worked on optimizing their free Linux drivers for performance approaching their Windows counterparts, especially on Sandy Bridge and newer hardware where performance optimizations have allowed the Intel driver to outperform their proprietary Windows drivers in certain tasks, in 2011.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Some of the performance enhancements may also benefit users of older hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Support for Intel's LLC (Last Level Cache, L4-Cache, Crystalwell and Iris Pro) was added in Linux kernel 3.12.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In 2013, the company had 20 to 30 full-time Linux graphics developers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Matrox develops and manufactures the Matrox Mystique, Parhelia, G200, G400 and G550.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Although the company provides free and open-source drivers for their chipsets which are older than the G550; chipsets newer than the G550 are supported by a closed-source driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] S3 Graphics develops the S3 Trio, ViRGE, Savage and Chrome, supported by OpenChrome.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Arm Ltd is a fabless semiconductor company which licenses semiconductor intellectual property cores.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Although they are known for the licensing the ARM instruction set and CPUs based on it, they also develop and license the Mali series of GPUs, and more recently Imortalis GPUs that support ray-tracing.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] On January 21, 2012, Phoronix reported that Luc Verhaegen was driving a reverse-engineering attempt aimed at the Arm Mali series of GPUs (specifically, the Mali-200 and Mali-400 versions).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The reverse-engineering project, known as Lima, was presented at FOSDEM on February 4, 2012.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] On February 2, 2013, Verhaegen demonstrated *Quake III Arena* in timedemo mode, running on top of the Lima driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In May 2018, a Lima developer posted the driver for inclusion in the Linux kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] As of May 2019, the Lima driver is part of the mainline Linux kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Panfrost is an open-source driver stack for Mali (and Immortalis) GPUs, covering Txxx (Midgard) and newer generations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] A talk introducing Panfrost was presented at X.Org Developer's Conference 2018.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] As of May 2019, the Panfrost kernel driver is part of the mainline Linux kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The userspace side consists of Mesa's Panfrost driver that provides OpenGL ES and OpenGL; as well as the PanVK userspace driver that provides Vulkan.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Collabora developed the Panthor kernel driver for third-generation and newer Valhall GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Panfrost and PanVK userspace drivers in Mesa use the Panthor kernel driver on these GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Later, Collabora announced the Tyr kernel driver, a joint effort between Collabora, Arm, and Google, written in Rust and designed to eventually replace the Panthor kernel driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Imagination Technologies is a fabless semiconductor company which develops and licenses semiconductor intellectual property cores, among which are the PowerVR GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Intel has manufactured a number of PowerVR-based GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] PowerVR GPUs are widely used in mobile system on a chip (SoC) devices.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Due to its wide use in embedded devices, the Free Software Foundation has put reverse-engineering of the PowerVR driver on its high-priority project list.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] As of March 2022, Imagination has provided a FOSS driver for its Rogue architecture-based PowerVR GX6250 from 2014, and its more recent A-Series architecture-based AXE-1-16M and BXS-4-64 GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Vivante Corporation is a fabless semiconductor company which licenses semiconductor intellectual property cores and develops the GCxxxx series of GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] A Vivante proprietary, closed-source Linux driver consists of kernel- and user-space parts.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Although the kernel component is open-source (GPL), the user-space components—consisting of the GLES(2) implementations and a HAL library—are not; these contain the bulk of the driver logic.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Wladimir J. van der Laan found and documented the state bits, command stream and shader ISA by studying how the blobs work, examining and manipulating command-stream dumps.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Etnaviv Gallium3D driver is being written based on this documentation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Van der Laan's work was inspired by the Lima driver, and the project has produced a functional-but-unoptimized Gallium3D LLVM driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Etnaviv driver has performed better than Vivante's proprietary code in some benchmarks, and it supports Vivante's GC400, GC800, GC1000, GC2000, GC3000 and GC7000 series.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In January 2017, Etnaviv was added to Mesa with both OpenGL ES 2.0 and Desktop OpenGL 2.1 support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Qualcomm develops the Adreno (formerly ATI Imageon) mobile GPU series, and includes it as part of their Snapdragon mobile SoC series.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Phoronix and Slashdot reported in 2012 that Rob Clark, inspired by the Lima driver, was working on reverse-engineering drivers for the Adreno GPU series.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In a referenced blog post, Clark wrote that he was doing the project in his spare time and that the Qualcomm platform was his only viable target for working on open 3D graphics.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] His employers (Texas Instruments and Linaro) were affiliated with the Imagination PowerVR and ARM Mali cores, which would have been his primary targets; he had working command streams for 2D support, and 3D commands seemed to have the same characteristics.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The driver code was published on Gitorious "freedreno", and has been moved to Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In 2012, a working shader assembler was completed; demonstration versions were developed for texture mapping and phong shading, using the reverse-engineered shader compiler.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Clark demonstrated Freedreno running desktop compositing, the XBMC media player and Quake III Arena at FOSDEM on February 2, 2013.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In August 2013, the kernel component of freedreno (MSM driver) was accepted into mainline and is available in Linux kernel 3.12 and later.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The DDX driver gained support for server-managed file descriptors requiring X.Org Server version 1.16 and above in July 2014.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In January 2016, the Mesa Gallium3D-style driver gained support for Adreno 430; in November of that year, the driver added support for the Adreno 500 series.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Freedreno can be used on devices such as 96Boards Dragonboard 410c and Nexus 7 (2013) in traditional Linux distributions (like Debian and Fedora) and on Android.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Broadcom develops and designs the VideoCore GPU series as part of their SoCs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Since it is used by the Raspberry Pi, there has been considerable interest in a FOSS driver for VideoCore.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Raspberry Pi Foundation, in co-operation with Broadcom, announced on October 24, 2012, that they open-sourced "all the ARM (CPU) code that drives the GPU".
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] However, the announcement was misleading; according to the author of the reverse-engineered Lima driver, the newly open-sourced components only allowed message-passing between the ARM CPU and VideoCore but offered little insight into Videocore and little additional programability.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Videocore GPU runs an RTOS which handles the processing; video acceleration is done with RTOS firmware coded for its proprietary GPU, and the firmware was not open-sourced on that date.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Since there was neither a toolchain targeting the proprietary GPU nor a documented instruction set, no advantage could be taken if the firmware source code became available.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Videocoreiv project attempted to document the VideoCore GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] On February 28, 2014 (the Raspberry Pi's second anniversary), Broadcom and the Raspberry Pi Foundation announced the release of full documentation for the VideoCore IV graphics core and a complete source release of the graphics stack under a 3-clause BSD license.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The free-license 3D graphics code was committed to Mesa on 29 August 2014, and first appeared on Mesa's 10.3 release.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Although Silicon Integrated Systems and VIA Technologies have expressed limited interest in open-source drivers, both have released source code which has been integrated into X.Org by FOSS developers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In July 2008, VIA opened documentation of their products to improve its image in the Linux and open-source communities.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The company has failed to work with the open-source community to provide documentation and a working DRM driver, leaving expectations of Linux support unfulfilled.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] On January 6, 2011, it was announced that VIA was no longer interested in supporting free graphics initiatives.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] DisplayLink announced an open-source project, Libdlo, with the goal of bringing support for their USB graphics technology to Linux and other platforms.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Its code is available under the LGPL license, but it has not been integrated into an X.Org driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] DisplayLink graphics support is available through the kernel udlfb driver (with fbdev) in mainline and udl/drm driver, which in March 2012 was only available in the drm-next tree.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Non-hardware-related vendors may also assist free graphics initiatives.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Red Hat has two full-time employees (David Airlie and Jérôme Glisse) working on Radeon software, and the Fedora Project sponsors a Fedora Graphics Test Week event before the launch of their new Linux distribution versions to test free graphics drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Other companies which have provided development or support include Novell and VMware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] Project VGA aims to create a low-budget, open-source VGA-compatible video card.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Open Graphics Project aimed to create an open-hardware GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] In September 2010, the first 25 OGD1 boards were made available for grant application and purchase.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Milkymist system on a chip, targeted at embedded graphics instead of desktop computers, supports a VGA output, a limited vertex shader and a 2D texturing unit.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] The Nyuzi, an experimental GPGPU processor, includes a synthesizable hardware design written in System Verilog, an instruction set emulator, an LLVM-based C-C++ compiler, software libraries and tests and explores parallel software and hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] It can run on a Terasic DE2-115 field-programmable gate array board.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] If a project uses FPGAs, it generally has a partially (or completely) closed-source toolchain.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] There are currently a couple of open-source toolchains available, however, for Lattice-based FPGAs (notably for iCE40 and ECP5 boards) which utilize Project IceStorm, and Trellis, respectively.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/free-and-open-source-graphics-device-driver] There is also a larger, ongoing effort to create the "GCC of FPGAs" called SymbiFlow which includes the aforementioned FPGA toolchains as well as an early-stage open-source toolchain for Xilinx-based FPGAs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] On Linux systems, GPU acceleration is provided primarily through Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] AMD supports the RadeonSI and RADV drivers in Mesa as their official GPU drivers on Linux.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Intel has only ever supported the Mesa drivers on Linux systems.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Google uses the Freedreno driver in Mesa in some Chromebooks with Qualcomm processors.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Systems with Nvidia cards usually use the proprietary Nvidia GeForce driver, but there are ongoing efforts to write Mesa Nvidia drivers called Nouveau and NVK.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] As of 2026, NVK is still usually slower than the proprietary driver, but the performance gap is continually decreasing as it is developed further.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Besides 3D applications such as games, modern display servers (X.org's Glamor or Wayland's Weston) use OpenGL/EGL; therefore all graphics typically go through Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa is hosted by freedesktop.org and was initiated in August 1993 by Brian Paul, who is still active in the project.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa was subsequently widely adopted and now contains numerous contributions from various individuals and corporations worldwide, including from most graphics hardware manufacturers, and other interested parties, such as Valve Corporation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa is known as housing implementations of graphic APIs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Historically the main API that Mesa has implemented is OpenGL, along with other Khronos Group related specifications (like OpenVG, OpenGL ES or recently EGL).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] But Mesa can implement other APIs and indeed it did with Glide (deprecated) and Direct3D 9 since July 2013.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa is also not specific to Unix-like operating systems: on Windows for example, Mesa provides an OpenGL API over DirectX.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa implements a translation layer between a graphics API such as OpenGL and the graphics hardware drivers in the operating system kernel.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The supported version of the different graphic APIs depends on the driver, because each hardware driver has its own implementation (and therefore status).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This is especially true for the "classic" drivers, while the Gallium3D drivers share common code that tend to homogenize the supported extensions and versions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa maintains a support matrix with the status of the current OpenGL conformance visualized at mesamatrix.net.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The Khronos Group officially announced Vulkan API in March 2015, and officially released Vulkan 1.0 on 16 February 2016.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Vulkan breaks compatibility with OpenGL and completely abandons its monolithic state machine concept.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The developers of Gallium3D called Vulkan to be something along the lines of Gallium3D 2.0 – Gallium3D separates the code that implements the OpenGL state machine from the code that is specific to the hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Version 1.3 is immediately available with Mesa 22.0.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Hardware with support of OpenGL ES 3.1 should run at Vulkan Level 1.3 and before.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] As Gallium3D ingests TGSI, Vulkan ingests SPIR-V (Standard Portable Intermediate Representation version "V" as in "Vulkan").
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Intel released their implementation of a Vulkan driver for their hardware the day the specification was officially released, but it was only mainlined in April and so became part of Mesa 12.0, released in July 2016.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] While already the i965 driver wasn't written according to the Gallium3D specifications, for the Vulkan driver it makes even less sense to flange it on top of Gallium3D.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Similarly there is no technical reason to flange it with NIR, but yet Intel's employees implemented their Vulkan driver that way.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] It is to be expected that AMD's own proprietary Vulkan driver, which was released in March, and was announced to be released as free and open-source software in the future and be mainlined into Mesa, also abandons Gallium3D.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] RADV is a free project for AMD and is available since version 13.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Conformance with Khronos-Test came in version 17.3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Actual is Full support of Vulkan 1.0 and 1.1 since Mesa 18.1.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Nvidia released their proprietary GeForce driver with Vulkan support at launch day and Imagination Technologies (PowerVR), Qualcomm (Adreno) and ARM (Mali) have done the same or at least announced proprietary Vulkan drivers for Android and other operating systems.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] But when and whether additional free and open-source Vulkan implementations for these GPUs will show up, remains to be seen.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa Software Driver VIRGL starts Vulkan Development in 2018 with GSOC projects for support of Virtual machines.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Lavapipe is a CPU-based Software Vulkan driver and the brother of LLVMpipe.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Google introduces Venus Vulkan Driver for virtual machines in Mesa 21.1 with full support for Vulkan 1.2+.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Qualcomm Turnip and Broadcom v3dv are new drivers for Qualcomm Adreno and Broadcom Raspberry 4 Hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Turnip is the Vulkan brother of freedreno for OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] V3dv supports Vulkan 1.0+ since Mesa 20.3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] In Version 21.1 Turnip supports Vulkan 1.1+.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Panfrost PanVK for ARM Mali is at way to Vulkan 1.1, but only 1.0 is stable available with Mesa 22.0.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Project Dozen is connecting direct 3D 12 (d3d12) with Vulkan for Linux Emulation WSL2 in Windows 10 and 11.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] In Mesa 23.2 Vulkan 1.0 is full conformant supported and 80% of 1.1 and 1.2 (mesamatrix).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] A kind of memory barrier that separates one buffer from the rest of the memory is called a fence.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Fences are there to ensure that a buffer is not being overwritten before rendering and display operations have completed on it.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Implicit fencing is used for synchronization between graphics drivers and the GPU hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The fence signals when a buffer is no longer being used by one component so it can be operated on or reused by another.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] In the past the Linux kernel had an implicit fencing mechanism, where a fence is directly attached to a buffer (cf.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] GEM handles and FDs), but userspace is unaware of this.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Explicit fencing exposes fences to userspace, where userspace gets fences from both the Direct Rendering Manager (DRM) subsystem and from the GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Explicit fencing is required by Vulkan and offers advantages for tracing and debugging.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Linux kernel 4.9 added Android's synchronization framework to mainline.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Generic Buffer Management (GBM) is an API that provides a mechanism for allocating buffers for graphics rendering tied to Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] GBM is intended to be used as a native platform for EGL on DRM or openwfd.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The handle it creates can be used to initialize EGL and to create render target buffers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa GBM is an abstraction of the graphics driver specific buffer management APIs (for instance the various libdrm_* libraries), implemented internally by calling into the Mesa GPU drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] For example, the Wayland compositor Weston does its rendering using OpenGL ES 2, which it initializes by calling EGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Since the server runs on the "bare KMS driver", it uses the EGL DRM platform, which could really be called the GBM platform, since it relies on the Mesa GBM interface.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] At XDC2014, Nvidia employee Andy Ritger proposed to enhance EGL in order to replace GBM.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This was not taken positively by the community, and Nvidia eventually changed their mind, and took another approach.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa, which runs in user-space, houses the implementations of several APIs for software, e.g.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] For example, Nouveau, which has been developed as part of Mesa, but also includes a Linux kernel component, which is being developed as part of the Linux kernel, supports the PureVideo-branded ASICs and provides access to them through VDPAU and partly through XvMC.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The free radeon driver supports Unified Video Decoder and Video Coding Engine through VDPAU and OpenMAX.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] V4L2 is a kernel-to-user-space interface for video bit streams delivered by webcams or TV tuners.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Due to patent concerns regarding the H.264, H.265 and VC-1 video codecs, Fedora Linux disabled support for VAAPI acceleration for those in its build of Mesa in September 2022.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The available free and open-source device drivers for graphic chipsets are "stewarded" by Mesa (because the existing free and open-source implementation of APIs are developed inside of Mesa).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Currently there are two frameworks to write graphics drivers: "classic" and Gallium3D.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] An overview over some (but not all) of the drivers available in Mesa is given at mesamatrix.net.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] There are device drivers for AMD/ATI R100 to R800, Intel, and Nvidia cards with 3D acceleration.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Previously drivers existed for the IBM/Toshiba/Sony Cell processor of the PlayStation 3, S3 Virge & Savage chipsets, VIA chipsets, Matrox G200 & G400, and more.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The free and open-source drivers compete with proprietary closed-source drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Depending on the availability of hardware documentation and man-power, the free and open-source driver lag behind more or less in supporting 3D acceleration of new hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Also, 3D rendering performance was usually significantly slower with some notable exceptions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Today this is still true for Nouveau for most NVIDIA GPUs while on AMDs Radeon GPUs the open driver now mostly matches or exceeds the proprietary driver's performance.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] At the time 3D graphics cards became more mainstream for PCs, individuals partly supported by some companies began working on adding more support for hardware-accelerated 3D rendering to Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The Direct Rendering Infrastructure (DRI) was one of these approaches to interface Mesa, OpenGL and other 3D rendering API libraries with the device drivers and hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] After reaching a basic level of usability, DRI support was officially added to Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This significantly broadened the available range of hardware support achievable when using the Mesa library.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] With adapting to DRI, the Mesa library finally took over the role of the front end component of a full scale OpenGL framework with varying backend components that could offer different degrees of 3D hardware support while not dropping the full software rendering capability.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The total system used many different software components.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] While the design requires all these components to interact carefully, the interfaces between them are relatively fixed.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Nonetheless, as most components interacting with the Mesa stack are open source, experimental work is often done through altering several components at once as well as the interfaces between them.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] If such experiments prove successful, they can be incorporated into the next major or minor release.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] That applies e.g. to the update of the DRI specification developed in the 2007-2008 timeframe.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The result of this experimentation, DRI2, operates without locks and with improved back buffer support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] For this, a special git branch of Mesa was created.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] DRI3 is supported by the Intel driver since 2013 and is default in some Linux distributions since 2016 to enable Vulkan support and more.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] It is also default on AMD hardware since late 2016 (X.Org Server 1.18.3 and newer).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa also contains multiple implementations of software rendering, *softpipe*, *llvmpipe*, and *lavapipe*, that allow OpenGL, Vulkan, and more to run on the CPU as a fallback when no graphics hardware accelerators are present.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] VirGL is a Rasterizer for Virtual machines implemented in Mesa 11.1 since 2015 with OpenGL 3.3 support and showed in Mesamatrix since Mesa 18.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] In actual new Mesa 18.2 it supports more than the others with OpenGL 4.3 and OpenGL ES 3.2.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] About 80% of OpenGL 4.4 and 4.5 features are also now ready.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Vulkan Development starts with GSOC 2018 projects.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Actual virGL state in Mesamatrix is full support of OpenGL 4.6+ and OpenGL ES 3.2+ with some necessary Linux software.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] D3d12 is a project of Microsoft for WSL2 emulation of OpenGL 3.3+ and OpenCL 1.2+ with Direct3D 12.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Actual state in Mesa 23.1 is OpenGL 4.2+ with nearly 4.4+ and OpenGL ES 3.1+.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Venus is a new Vulkan VirtIO GPU Driver for GPU in virtual machines by Google.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Venus is merged in 21.1 and for public in 21.2 introduced.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Venus supports Vulkan 1.3+ in Mesa 23.1.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Hardware minimum is Vulkan 1.1 with some extensions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The idea of bundling multiple drivers into a single "mega" driver was proposed by Emma Anholt.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] It allows for a single copy of the shared Mesa code to be used among multiple drivers (instead of it existing in each driver separately) and offering better performance than a separate shared library due to the removal of the internal library interface.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The state trackers for VDPAU and XvMC have become separate libraries.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] shader-db is a collection of about 20,000 shaders gathered from various computer games and benchmarks as well as some scripts to compile these and collect some statistics.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Shader-db is intended to help validate an optimization.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] It was noticed that an unexpected number of shaders are not hand-written but generated.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This means these shaders were originally written in HLSL and then translated into GLSL by some translator program, such as e.g.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The problem is, that the generated code is often far from being optimal.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Matt Turner said it was much easier to fix this in the translator program than having to make Mesa's compiler carry the burden of dealing with such bloated shaders.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] shader-db cannot be considered free and open-source software.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] To use it legally, one must have a license for all the computer games that the shaders are part of.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The so-called "user-mode graphics device drivers" (UMD) in Mesa have very few commonalities with what is generally called a device driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] One goal of Mesa is the optimization of code that is to be executed by the respective GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Instead of documenting the pieces of software, this article shall instead look at the Intermediate Representations used in the process of compiling and optimizing.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] See Abstract syntax tree (AST) and Static single assignment form (SSA form).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] SPIR-V is a certain version of the Standard Portable Intermediate Representation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The idea is, that graphics applications output SPIR-V instead of GLSL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] In contrast to the latter, SPIR-V is binary to avoid implementation differences between GLSL compiler frontends of different driver implementations, as this has been a major source of application incompatibilities and bugs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Also SPIR-V binary usually also passed through some general optimizations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] A UMD needs only apply optimizations, that are specific to the supported hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] NIR (New Internal Representation) was introduced to overcome TGSI limitations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] NIR was extended in last and actual releases as base of Spir-V support and is since 2016 main development area.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] LLVMpipe, i965, RadeonSI, Nouveau, freedreno, vc4 are changed to NIR from TGSI.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] RADV, Zink and other new drivers starts with NIR.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] All drivers with full OpenGL 4.6 support are related to NIR by SPIR-V support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Also AMD r600 has a fork with NIR for better support of HD5000 and HD6000 series.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This option for r600 is default since Mesa 21.0.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The Tungsten Graphics Shader Infrastructure (TGSI) was introduced in 2008 by Tungsten Graphics.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] NIR is now Main development area, so TGSI is only for older driver like r300g default infrastructure and will be deprecated in some years.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] GLSL-To-TGSI code will be deleted in Mesa 22.2.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Default is newer NIR-to-TGSI with GLSL-to-NIR for all native NIR drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Some older TGSI drivers are supported with this NIR Code path.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Later NIR-To-TGSI will be deprecated for native NIR drivers only.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] `llvmpipe` does not output machine code, but instead LLVM IR.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] From here on, LLVM does optimizations and the compilation to machine code.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This does mean, that a certain minimum version of LLVM has to be installed as well.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa's GLSL compiler generates its own IR.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Because each driver has very different requirements from a LIR, it differentiates between HIR (high-level IR) and LIR (low-level IR).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] A feature matrix is being provided at mesamatrix.net.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The development of Gallium3D started in 2008 at Tungsten Graphics, and the implementation is available as free and open-source software as part of Mesa 3D hosted by freedesktop.org.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The primary goal of making driver development easier, bundling otherwise duplicated code of several different drivers at a single point, and to support modern hardware architectures.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This is done by providing a better division of labor, for example, leaving memory management to the kernel DRI driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Gallium3D has been a part of Mesa since 2009 and is used by all non-Vulkan drivers as of version 22.0.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] As of 2026, there are at least 20 Gallium3D drivers, including hardware drivers, software implementations, virtualization passthrough, and translation layers implementing Gallium3D on top of APIs such as Vulkan, Apple's Metal API, and Microsoft's Direct3D 12.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Gallium3D eases programming of device drivers by splitting the graphics device driver into three parts.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This is accomplished by the introduction of two interfaces: *Gallium3D State Tracker Interface* and the *Gallium3D WinSys Interface*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Each State Tracker contains an implementation of the Gallium3D State Tracker Interface, and is used by all existent Gallium3D hardware device drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] This is the actual code that is specific to the underlying 3D graphic accelerator, but only as far as the Gallium3D WinSys Interface allows.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] There is a unique Gallium3D hardware device driver for each available graphics chip and each implements the Gallium3D State Tracker Interface as well as the Gallium3D WinSys Interface.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The Gallium3D hardware device driver understands NIR (NIR Intermediate Representation, a recursive acronym), an intermediate language for describing shaders.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] and each one implements the Gallium3D WinSys Interface to interface with all available Gallium3D hardware device drivers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Gallium3D provides a unified API exposing standard hardware functions, such as shader units found on modern hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Thus, 3D APIs such as OpenGL 1.x/2.x, OpenGL 3.x, OpenVG, GPGPU infrastructure or even Direct3D (as found in the Wine compatibility layer) will need only a single back-end, called a state tracker, targeting the Gallium3D API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] By contrast, legacy DRI device drivers required a different back-end for each hardware platform, and several other APIs needed translation to OpenGL, at the expense of code duplication.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] All vendor device drivers, due to their proprietary and closed-source nature, are written that way meaning that, e.g. the AMD Catalyst implements both OpenGL and Direct3D, and the vendor drivers for the GeForce have their implementations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Under Gallium3D, Direct Rendering Manager (DRM) kernel drivers will manage the memory and Direct Rendering Interface (DRI2) drivers will be more GPU processing oriented.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Tungsten Graphics Shader Infrastructure (TGSI) is an Intermediate representation used within some parts of Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Shaders written in OpenGL Shading Language are to be translated/compiled into TGSI, then optimizations are made, and then the TGSI shaders are being compiled into shaders for the instruction set of the used GPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] As of 2026, most drivers have moved away from TGSI, in favor of NIR.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] NIR is the primary Intermediate Representation in Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Development of NIR started in 2014 inside Intel, and over time NIR has replaced TGSI in most parts of Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Original authors of Gallium3D were Keith Whitwell and Brian Paul at Tungsten Graphics (acquired by VMware in 2008).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Nouveau development is done exclusively for the Gallium framework.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The old DRI driver was removed from the master branch of the Mesa repository on Freedesktop.org.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The gallium-0.2 branch was merged into mainline Master branch of Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Gallium3D can run on Linux as well as FreeBSD kernels.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] to be hardware-accelerated by any Gallium3D-based driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa3D 7.5 is released, the first version to include Gallium3D.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Initial support for the Evergreen GPUs was added to the r600g driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] There are two Gallium3D drivers for ATI hardware known as r300g and r600g for R300-R500 and R600-Evergreen GPUs respectively.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Major commits were made to the code to support Direct3D 10 and 11.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] In time, this might offer the ability to use recent Direct3D implementations on Linux systems.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Intel 965g and Cell Gallium drivers were removed from the master branch of Mesa as unmaintained and broken.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Major commits were made to the code to support Direct3D 9.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa 21.2 released with new Intel Crocus driver, based on Gallium3D, supporting Intel Sandy Bridge through Haswell iGPUs, replacing the need for the old non-Gallium3D i965 driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Also added was the PanVK Vulkan Driver for ARM Mali GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mature drivers in Mesa can often out-perform the proprietary drivers for that same hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Particularly on handheld gaming devices that are significantly constrained in both power and thermals, running Linux with Mesa drivers has been shown to consistently and significantly out-perform Windows with the manufacturer's proprietary drivers on the same hardware, sometimes by as much as 75%.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Microsoft allegedly set an internal goal of being able to match the performance of SteamOS on handheld gaming devices.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Project initiator Brian Paul was a graphics hobbyist.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] He thought it would be fun to implement a simple 3D graphics library using the OpenGL API, which he might then use instead of VOGL (very ordinary GL Like Library).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Beginning in 1993, he spent eighteen months of part-time development before he released the software on the Internet in February 1995.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The software was well received, and people began contributing to its development.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa started off by rendering all 3D computer graphics on the CPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Despite this, the internal architecture of Mesa was designed to be open for attaching to graphics processor-accelerated 3D rendering.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] In this first phase, rendering was done indirectly in the display server, leaving some overhead and noticeable speed lagging behind the theoretical maximum.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The Diamond Monster 3D, using the Voodoo Graphics chipset, was one of the first 3D hardware devices supported by Mesa.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The first true graphics hardware support was added to Mesa in 1997, based upon the Glide API for the then new 3dfx Voodoo I/II graphics cards and their successors.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] A major problem of using Glide as the acceleration layer was the habit of Glide to run full screen, which was only suitable for computer games.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Further, Glide took the lock of the screen memory, and thus the display server was blocked from doing any other GUI tasks.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa 10 complies with OpenGL 3.3 for Intel, AMD/ATI, and Nvidia GPU hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa 11 was announced with some drivers being OpenGL 4.1 compliant.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa 12 contains OpenGL 4.2 and 4.3 and Intel Vulkan 1.0 support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Mesa 13 brought Intel support for OpenGL 4.4 and 4.5 (all Features supported for Intel Gen 8+, Radeon GCN, Nvidia (Fermi, Kepler), but no Khronos-Test for 4.5-Label) and experimental AMD Vulkan 1.0 support through the community driver RADV.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] OpenGL ES 3.2 is possible with Intel Skylake (Gen9).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 1st stable version of 2017 is 17.0 (new year Counting).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Ready features are certified OpenGL 4.5, OpenGL 4.5 for Intel Haswell, OpenGL 4.3 for Nvidia Maxwell and Pascal (GM107+).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Huge performance gain was measured with Maxwell 1 (GeForce GTX 750 Ti and more with GM1xx).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Maxwell-2-Cards (GeForce GTX 980 and more with GM2xx) are underclocked without Nvidia information.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The Khronos CTS test suite for OpenGL 4.4, 4.5 and OpenGL ES 3.0+ is in now (2017-01-24) Open Source and all tests for Mesa 13 and 17 are now possible without costs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 2nd stable version of 2017, 17.1.0, came out on 10 May 2017 with some interesting improvements.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] OpenGL 4.2+ for Intel Ivy Bridge and OpenGL 3.3+ for Intel Open SWR Rasterizer are 2 of the highlights.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Due to the modularized nature of OpenGL, Mesa can support extensions from newer versions of OpenGL without claiming full support for such versions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] For example, in July 2016, Mesa supported OpenGL ES 3.1 but also all OpenGL ES 3.2 extensions except for five, as well as a number of extensions not part of any OpenGL or OpenGL ES version.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 3rd Version 17.2 is available since September 2017 with some new OpenGL 4.6 features and velocity improvements in 3D for Intel and AMD.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Only 1.4% of Tests fail for OpenGL 4.5 in Nouveau for Kepler.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 4th Version 17.3 is ready since December 2017.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Many improvements in many drivers are available.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] OpenGL 4.6 is nearly fully available (Spir-V is not ready).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] AMD Vulkan Driver RADV is now fully conformant in Khronos-Test.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 1st version of 2018 is 18.0 and available since March 2018 by same scheme in 2017.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Full OpenGL 4.6 support is not ready, but many features and improvements were successfully tested in RC3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 10-bit support for Intel i965 in Colors is also a Highlight.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] New is support for Intel Cannon Lake and AMD Vega with actual Linux Version.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] AMD Evergreen Chips (RV800 or R900) are near OpenGL 4.5 support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Old AMD R600 or RV700 Chips can only support OpenGL 3.3 with some features of OpenGL 4.x.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Freedreno is the Driver for Adreno Hardware and near OpenGL 3.3 support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 2nd version of 2018 is 18.1 and available since May.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Target is Vulkan 1.1.72 in Intel ANV and AMD RADV driver.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] OpenGL 4.6 with spir-V is also main target.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Permanent work is possible completion of Features and Optimization of drivers for older hardware like AMD R600/Evergreen, Nvidia Tesla and before, Fermi, Kepler or Intel Sandybridge, Ivybridge, Haswell or Broadwell.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] ARM Architecture made also great improvements in Adreno 3xx/4xx/5xx and Broadwell VC4/VC5 for Raspi with main target OpenGL ES.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 3rd version of 2018 is 18.2 and available in calendar stable in September.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] OpenGL 4.6 with spir-V and Vulkan 1.1.80 are in WIP.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] The soft Driver for virtual machines VIRGL is ready for OpenGL 4.3 and OpenGL ES 3.2.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] RadeonSI is also ready for OpenGL ES 3.2.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] ASTC Texture Compression Support and Compatibility Modus Support for OpenGL 4.4 (3.1 in 18.1) are other highlights in RadeonSI for AMD GCN Cards.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] New Vulkan 1.1 and more features for Intel and AMD are available.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] See more Details for Vulkan in Mesamatrix.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 4th version of 2018 is 18.3 and released as stable Version 18.3.1 in December 2018.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Many features in Detail and support of newer hardware are main parts.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] Full support of OpenGL 4.6 is not ready.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/gallium3d] 1st Version of 2019 is 19.0 and was now released at March.
