[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] (SGI) began developing OpenGL in 1991 and released it on June 30, 1992.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It is used for a variety of applications, including computer-aided design (CAD), video games, scientific visualization, virtual reality, and flight simulation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Since 2006, OpenGL has been managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The OpenGL specification describes an abstract application programming interface (API) for drawing 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It is designed to be implemented mostly or entirely using hardware acceleration such as a GPU, although it is possible for the API to be implemented entirely in software running on a CPU.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The API is defined as a set of functions which may be called by the client program, alongside a set of named integer constants (for example, the constant GL_TEXTURE_2D, which corresponds to the decimal number 3553).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Although the function definitions are superficially similar to those of the programming language C, they are language-independent.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] As such, OpenGL has many language bindings, some of the most noteworthy being the JavaScript binding WebGL (API, based on OpenGL ES 2.0, for 3D rendering from within a web browser); the C bindings WGL, GLX and CGL; the C binding provided by iOS; and the Java and C bindings provided by Android.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In addition to being language-independent, OpenGL is also cross-platform.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The specification says nothing on the subject of obtaining and managing an OpenGL context, leaving this as a detail of the underlying windowing system.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] For the same reason, OpenGL is purely concerned with rendering, providing no APIs related to input, audio, or windowing.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] New versions of the OpenGL specifications are released by the Khronos Group, each of which extends the API to support various new features.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The details of each version are decided by consensus between the Group's members, including graphics card manufacturers, operating system designers, and general technology companies such as Mozilla and Google.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In addition to the features required by the core API, graphics processing unit (GPU) vendors may provide additional functionality in the form of *extensions*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Extensions may introduce new functions and new constants, and may relax or remove restrictions on existing OpenGL functions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Vendors can use extensions to expose custom APIs without needing support from other vendors or the Khronos Group as a whole, which greatly increases the flexibility of OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] All extensions are collected in, and defined by, the OpenGL Registry.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The features introduced by each new version of OpenGL are typically formed from the combined features of several widely implemented extensions, especially extensions of type ARB or EXT.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL is no longer in active development; whereas between 2001 and 2014, OpenGL specification was updated mostly on a yearly basis, with two releases (3.1 and 3.2) taking place in 2009 and three (3.3, 4.0 and 4.1) in 2010.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The latest OpenGL specification 4.6 was released in 2017 after a three-year break, and was limited to inclusion of eleven existing ARB and EXT extensions into the core profile.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Active development of OpenGL was dropped in favor of the Vulkan API, released in 2016, and codenamed glNext during initial development.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In 2017, Khronos Group announced that OpenGL ES would not have new versions and has since concentrated on development of Vulkan and other technologies.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] As a result, certain capabilities offered by modern GPUs, e.g. ray tracing, are not supported by the OpenGL standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] However, support for newer features might be provided through the vendor-specific OpenGL extensions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board released a series of manuals along with the specification which have been updated to track changes in the API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL Programming for the X Window System.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Includes a poster-sized fold-out diagram showing the structure of an idealised OpenGL implementation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL Programming for Windows 95 and Windows NT.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] A book about interfacing OpenGL with Microsoft Windows.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL's documentation is also accessible via its official webpage.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The earliest versions of OpenGL were released with a companion library called the OpenGL Utility Library (GLU).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It provided simple, useful features which were unlikely to be supported in contemporary hardware, such as tessellating, and generating mipmaps and primitive shapes.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The GLU specification was last updated in 1998 and depends on OpenGL features which are now deprecated.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Given that creating an OpenGL context is quite a complex process, and given that it varies between operating systems, automatic OpenGL context creation has become a common feature of several game-development and user-interface libraries, including SDL, Allegro, SFML, FLTK, and Qt.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] A few libraries have been designed solely to produce an OpenGL-capable window.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The first such library was OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT), later superseded by freeglut.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Given the high workload involved in identifying and loading OpenGL extensions, a few libraries have been designed which load all available extensions and functions automatically.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Examples include OpenGL Easy Extension library (GLEE), OpenGL Extension Wrangler Library (GLEW) and glbinding.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Extensions are also loaded automatically by most language bindings, such as Java OpenGL, PyOpenGL and WebGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Mesa 3D is an open-source implementation of OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It can do pure software rendering, and it may also use hardware acceleration on BSD, Linux, and other platforms by taking advantage of the Direct Rendering Infrastructure.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] As of version 20.0, it implements version 4.6 of the OpenGL standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In the 1980s, developing software that could function with a wide range of graphics hardware was a challenge without a cross-platform library.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Software developers wrote custom interfaces and drivers for each piece of hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] This was expensive and resulted in multiplication of effort.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] By the early 1990s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) was a leader in 3D graphics for workstations.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Their IRIS GL API became the industry standard, as IRIS GL was considered easier to use, and it supported immediate mode rendering, therefore being faster than competitors like PHIGS.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] SGI's competitors (including Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and IBM) were also able to bring to market 3D hardware supported by extensions made to the PHIGS standard, which pressured SGI to open source a version of IRIS GL as a public standard called **OpenGL**.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] However, SGI had many customers for whom the change from IRIS GL to OpenGL would demand significant investment.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Moreover, IRIS GL had API functions that were irrelevant to 3D graphics.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] For example, it included a windowing, keyboard and mouse API, in part because it was developed before the X Window System and Sun's NeWS.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] IRIS GL libraries were heavily tied into SGI's proprietary graphics hardware and could not be open sourced as-is due to hardware patents and trade secrets.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] These factors required SGI to continue to support the advanced and proprietary Iris Inventor and Iris Performer programming APIs while market support for OpenGL matured.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] One of the restrictions of IRIS GL was that it only provided access to features supported by the underlying hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] If the graphics hardware did not support a feature natively, then the application could not use it.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL overcame this problem by providing software implementations of features unsupported by hardware, allowing applications to use advanced graphics on relatively low-powered systems.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL standardized access to hardware, pushed the development responsibility of hardware interface programs (device drivers) to hardware manufacturers, and delegated windowing functions to the underlying operating system.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] With so many different kinds of graphics hardware, getting them all to speak the same language in this way had a remarkable impact by giving software developers a higher-level platform for 3D-software development.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In 1992, SGI led the creation of the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (OpenGL ARB), the group of companies that would maintain and expand the OpenGL specification in the future.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Two years later, they also played with the idea of releasing something called "OpenGL++" which included elements such as a scene-graph API (presumably based on their Performer technology).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The specification was circulated among a few interested parties – but never turned into a product.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Released in 1996, Microsoft's Direct3D eventually became the main competitor of OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Over 50 game developers signed an open letter to Microsoft, released on June 12, 1997, calling on the company to actively support OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] On December 17, 1997, Microsoft and SGI initiated the Fahrenheit project, which was a joint effort with the goal of unifying the OpenGL and Direct3D interfaces (and adding a scene-graph API too).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In 1998, Hewlett-Packard joined the project.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It initially showed some promise of bringing order to the world of interactive 3D computer graphics APIs, but on account of financial constraints at SGI, strategic reasons at Microsoft, and a general lack of industry support, it was abandoned in 1999.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In July 2006, the OpenGL Architecture Review Board voted to transfer control of the OpenGL API standard to the Khronos Group.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL was the standard for many CAD software (such as Blender) and games in the 1990s and 2000s, and faces wide support across virtually all hardware vendors.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Despite the emergence of newer graphics APIs like its successor Vulkan or Metal, OpenGL continues to be a widely used standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] This continued relevance is supported by several factors: ongoing development with new extensions and driver optimizations, its cross-platform compatibility, and the availability of compatibility layers like ANGLE and Zink.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] These layers allow OpenGL to run efficiently on top of Vulkan and Metal, offering a pathway for continued use or gradual transitions for developers.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] However, the graphics API landscape has been shifting, where some companies are moving away from OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In June 2018, Apple deprecated OpenGL APIs on all of their platforms (iOS, macOS and tvOS), encouraging developers to use their proprietary Metal API, which was introduced in 2014.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Game developers have also begun to adopt newer APIs. id Software, who has been using OpenGL in their games since the late 1990s in games such as GLQuake or some games of the Doom franchise, transitioned away to its successor Vulkan in its id Tech 7 engine in 2016.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] They first supported Vulkan in an update for their id Tech 6 engine.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The company's first licensed use of OpenGL was in its Quake II engine, also known as id Tech 2.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] In March 2023, Valve removed OpenGL support from Dota 2 in favor of Vulkan.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Atypical Games, with support from Samsung, updated their game engine to use Vulkan, rather than OpenGL, across all non-Apple platforms.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The Khronos Group, the consortium responsible for OpenGL's development, has stopped updating OpenGL, with the last release made in 2017.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It has not received a number of modern graphics technologies, such as hardware accelerated Ray Tracing, on-GPU video decoding, and advanced anti-aliasing algorithms like Nvidia DLSS and AMD FSR.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Another modern feature, Mesh Shaders, was initially only supported through an Nvidia exclusive extension, however in 2025, a cross-vendor OpenGL Mesh Shader extension was released.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Google's Fuchsia OS, while using Vulkan natively and requiring a Vulkan-conformant GPU, still intends to support OpenGL on top of Vulkan via the ANGLE translation layer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The first version of OpenGL, version 1.0, was released on June 30, 1992, by Mark Segal and Kurt Akeley.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Since then, OpenGL has occasionally been extended by releasing a new version of the specification.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Such releases define a baseline set of features which all conforming graphics cards must support, and against which new extensions can more easily be written.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Each new version of OpenGL tends to incorporate several extensions which have widespread support among graphics-card vendors, although the details of those extensions may be changed.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 2.0 was originally conceived by 3Dlabs to address concerns that OpenGL was stagnating and lacked a strong direction.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] 3Dlabs proposed a number of major additions to the standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Most of these were, at the time, rejected by the ARB or otherwise never came to fruition in the form that 3Dlabs proposed.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] However, their proposal for a C-style shading language was eventually completed, resulting in the current formulation of the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL or GLslang).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Like the assembly-like shading languages it was replacing, it allowed replacing the fixed-function vertex and fragment pipe with shaders, though this time written in a C-like high-level language.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The design of GLSL was notable for making relatively few concessions to the limits of the hardware then available.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] This harked back to the earlier tradition of OpenGL setting an ambitious, forward-looking target for 3D accelerators rather than merely tracking the state of currently available hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The final OpenGL 2.0 specification includes support for GLSL 1.10.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 2.1 adds support for Pixel Buffer Objects, sRGB textures and GLSL 1.20.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Before the release of OpenGL 3.0, the new revision had the codename Longs Peak.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] At the time of its original announcement, Longs Peak was presented as the first major API revision in OpenGL's lifetime.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It consisted of an overhaul to the way that OpenGL works, calling for fundamental changes to the API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The draft introduced a change to object management.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The GL 2.1 object model was built upon the state-based design of OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] That is, to modify an object or to use it, one needs to bind the object to the state system, then make modifications to the state or perform function calls that use the bound object.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Because of OpenGL's use of a state system, objects must be mutable.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] That is, the basic structure of an object can change at any time, even if the rendering pipeline is asynchronously using that object.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] A texture object can be redefined from 2D to 3D.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] This requires any OpenGL implementations to add a degree of complexity to internal object management.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Under the Longs Peak API, object creation would become atomic, using templates to define the properties of an object which would be created with one function call.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The object could then be used immediately across multiple threads.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Objects would also be immutable; however, they could have their contents changed and updated.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] For example, a texture could change its image, but its size and format could not be changed.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] To support backwards compatibility, the old state based API would still be available, but no new functionality would be exposed via the old API in later versions of OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] This would have allowed legacy code bases, such as the majority of CAD products, to continue to run while other software could be written against or ported to the new API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Longs Peak was initially due to be finalized in September 2007 under the name OpenGL 3.0, but the Khronos Group announced on October 30 that it had run into several issues that it wished to address before releasing the specification.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] As a result, the spec was delayed, and the Khronos Group went into a media blackout until the release of the final OpenGL 3.0 spec.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The final specification proved far less revolutionary than the Longs Peak proposal.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Instead of removing all immediate mode and fixed functionality (non-shader mode), the spec included them as deprecated features.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The proposed object model was not included, and no plans have been announced to include it in any future revisions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] As a result, the API remained largely the same with a few existing extensions being promoted to core functionality.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Among some developer groups this decision caused something of an uproar, with many developers professing that they would switch to DirectX in protest.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Most complaints revolved around the lack of communication by Khronos to the development community and multiple features being discarded that were viewed favorably by many.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Other frustrations included the requirement of DirectX 10 level hardware to use OpenGL 3.0 and the absence of geometry shaders and instanced rendering as core features.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Other sources reported that the community reaction was not quite as severe as originally presented, with many vendors showing support for the update.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 introduced a deprecation mechanism to simplify future revisions of the API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Certain features, marked as deprecated, could be completely disabled by requesting a *forward-compatible context* from the windowing system.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 features could still be accessed alongside these deprecated features, however, by requesting a *full context*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 8 Series and newer, ATI Radeon HD 2000 series and newer, Intel HD Graphics in Intel Sandy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 3.1 fully removed all of the features which were deprecated in version 3.0, with the exception of wide lines.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] From this version onwards, it's not possible to access new features using a *full context*, or to access deprecated features using a *forward-compatible context*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] An exception to the former rule is made if the implementation supports the ARB_compatibility extension, but this is not guaranteed.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: Mesa supports ARM Panfrost with Version 21.0.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 further built on the deprecation mechanisms introduced by OpenGL 3.0, by dividing the specification into a *core profile* and *compatibility profile*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Compatibility contexts include the previously removed fixed-function APIs, equivalent to the ARB_compatibility extension released alongside OpenGL 3.1, while core contexts do not.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 also included an upgrade to GLSL version 1.50.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 3.3 includes minor additions, with the goal of retaining as much functionality as possible from OpenGL 4.0, while keeping support for older hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Additions include new blending functions, Sampler Objects and new texture and vertex formats.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Support is also added for GLSL version 3.30, major and minor versions now match with OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] OpenGL 4.0 was released alongside version 3.3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] It was designed for hardware able to support Direct3D 11.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] As in OpenGL 3.0, this version of OpenGL contains a high number of fairly inconsequential extensions, designed to thoroughly expose the abilities of Direct3D 11-class hardware, such as tessellation.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Ivy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge and newer).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Additionally, this is the last core profile supported by Apple macOS.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), and Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge without stencil texturing, Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] VIRGL Emulation for virtual machines supports 4.3+ with Mesa 20.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1, and Tegra X1.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 7000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel Skylake and newer, Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Apple deprecated OpenGL in iOS 12 and macOS 10.14 Mojave in favor of Metal, but it is still available as of macOS 15 Sequoia (including on Apple silicon devices).
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The latest version supported for OpenGL is 4.1 from 2011.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] A proprietary library from Molten – authors of MoltenVK – called MoltenGL, can translate OpenGL calls to Metal.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] There are several projects that attempt to implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The Vulkan backend for Google's ANGLE achieved OpenGL ES 3.1 conformance in July 2020.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The Mesa3D project also includes such a driver, called *Zink*.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Microsoft's Windows 11 on Arm added support for OpenGL 3.3 via GLon12, an open source OpenGL implementation on top DirectX 12 via Mesa Gallium.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] Vulkan, formerly named the "Next Generation OpenGL Initiative" (glNext), is a ground-up redesign effort to unify OpenGL and OpenGL ES into one common API that will not be backwards compatible with existing OpenGL versions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/opengl] The initial version of Vulkan API was released on February 16, 2016.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan is intended to offer higher performance and more efficient CPU and GPU usage compared to the older OpenGL and Direct3D 11 APIs, by providing a considerably lower-level API that more closely resembles how modern GPUs work.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan is comparable to Apple's Metal API and Microsoft's Direct3D 12.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] In addition to its lower CPU usage, Vulkan is designed to allow developers to better distribute work among multiple CPU cores.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan was first announced by the non-profit Khronos Group at GDC 2015.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] The Vulkan API was initially referred to as the "next generation OpenGL initiative", or "OpenGL next" by Khronos, but use of those names was discontinued when "Vulkan" was announced.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan is derived from and built upon components of AMD's Mantle API, which was donated by AMD to Khronos with the intent of giving Khronos a foundation on which to begin developing a low-level API that they could standardize across the industry.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan is intended to provide a variety of advantages over other APIs as well as over its predecessor, OpenGL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan offers lower overhead, more direct control over the GPU, and lower CPU usage.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Its overall concept and feature set are similar to those of Mantle.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] They were later adopted by Microsoft with Direct3D 12 and by Apple with Metal.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan is available on multiple modern operating systems and architectures, and provides a single API for both desktop and mobile graphics devices, whereas previously these were split between OpenGL and OpenGL ES respectively.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Like OpenGL, and in contrast to Direct3D 12, the Vulkan API is not locked to a single OS or device form factor.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan runs natively on at least Android, Linux, BSD Unix, QNX, Haiku, Nintendo Switch, Raspberry Pi, Stadia, Fuchsia, Tizen, and Windows 7, 8, 10, and 11.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] MoltenVK provides freely licensed third-party support for macOS, iOS and tvOS by wrapping over Apple's Metal API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan reduces load on CPUs through the use of batching and other low-level optimizations, thereby reducing CPU workloads and leaving the CPU free to do more computation or rendering than would otherwise be possible.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Direct3D 11 and OpenGL 4 were initially designed for use with single-core CPUs and only received augmentation to be executed on multi-cores.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Even when application developers use the augmentations, these APIs regularly do not scale well on multi-cores.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan offers improved scalability on multi-core CPUs due to the modernized threading architecture.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] OpenGL uses the high-level language GLSL for writing shaders, which forces each OpenGL driver to implement its own compiler for GLSL.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] This then executes at application runtime to translate the program's shaders into the GPU's machine code.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] In contrast, Vulkan drivers are supposed to ingest shaders already translated into an intermediate binary format called SPIR-V (Standard Portable Intermediate Representation), analogous to the binary format that HLSL shaders are compiled into in Direct3D.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] By allowing shader pre-compilation, application initialization speed is improved and a larger variety of shaders can be used per scene.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] A Vulkan driver only needs to perform GPU specific optimization and code generation, resulting in easier driver maintenance, and potentially smaller driver packages.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] The developers of applications now can also more easily obfuscate proprietary shader code, due to shaders not being stored directly as source code.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] However, tools are provided that can decompile SPIR-V to human-readable high-level code.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] AMD states that "Vulkan supports close-to-metal control, enabling faster performance and better image quality across Windows 7, Windows 8.1, Windows 10, and Linux.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan 1.0 was released in February 2016.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] At SIGGRAPH 2016, Khronos announced that Vulkan would be getting support for automatic multi-GPU features, similar to what is offered by Direct3D 12.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Multi-GPU support included in-API removes the need for SLI or Crossfire, which requires graphics cards to be of the same model.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] API multi-GPU instead allows the API to intelligently split the workload among two or more completely different GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] For example, integrated GPUs included on the CPU can be used in conjunction with a high-end dedicated GPU for a slight performance boost.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On March 7, 2018, Vulkan 1.1 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] This first major update to the API standardized several extensions, such as multi-view, device groups, cross-process and cross-API sharing, advanced compute functionality, HLSL support, and YCbCr support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] At the same time, it brought better compatibility with DirectX 12, explicit multi-GPU support, (optional extensions for supporting hardware, e.g. some Nvidia GPUs, on e.g.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Windows and Android) ray tracing support, and laid the groundwork for the next generation of GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Alongside Vulkan 1.1, SPIR-V was updated to version 1.3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On January 15, 2020, Vulkan 1.2 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] This second major update to the API integrates 23 additional commonly used proven Vulkan extensions into the base Vulkan standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] The additional features of Vulkan 1.2 improve its flexibility when it comes to implementing other graphics APIs on top of Vulkan, including "uniform buffer standard layout", "scalar block layout", and "separate stencil usage".
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On January 25, 2022, Vulkan 1.3 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] This third major update to the API integrates 23 additional commonly used proven Vulkan extensions into the base Vulkan standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan 1.3 focuses on reducing fragmentation by making the new features not optional in order for a device to be considered Vulkan 1.3 capable.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] The new features in Vulkan 1.3 include dynamic rendering, additional dynamic state, improved synchronization API, and device profiles.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On December 3, 2024, Vulkan 1.4 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] When releasing OpenCL 2.2, the Khronos Group announced that OpenCL would converge where possible with Vulkan to enable OpenCL software deployment flexibility over both APIs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] This has been now demonstrated by Adobe's Premiere Rush using the clspv open source compiler to compile significant amounts of OpenCL C kernel code to run on a Vulkan runtime for deployment on Android.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] The Khronos Group began a project to create a next generation graphics API in July 2014 with a kickoff meeting at Valve.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] At SIGGRAPH 2014, the project was publicly announced with a call for participants.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] According to the US Patent and Trademark Office, the trademark for Vulkan was filed on February 19, 2015.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan was formally named and announced at Game Developers Conference 2015, although speculation and rumors centered around a new API existed beforehand and referred to it as "**glNext**".
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] In early 2015, LunarG (funded by Valve) developed and showcased a Linux driver for Intel which enabled Vulkan compatibility on the HD 4000 series integrated graphics, despite the open-source Mesa drivers not being fully compatible with OpenGL 4.0 until later that year.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] There is still the possibility of Sandy Bridge support, since it supports compute through Direct3D11.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On August 10, 2015, Google announced that future versions of Android would support Vulkan.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Android 7.x "Nougat" launched support for Vulkan on August 22, 2016.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On December 18, 2015, the Khronos Group announced that the 1.0 version of the Vulkan specification was nearly complete and would be released when conforming drivers were available.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] The full Vulkan specification and the open-source Vulkan SDK were released on February 16, 2016.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On February 26, 2018, Khronos Group announced that the Vulkan API became available to all on macOS and iOS through the MoltenVK library, which enables Vulkan to run on top of Metal.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Other new developments were shown at SIGGRAPH 2018.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Previously MoltenVK was a proprietary and commercially licensed solution, but Valve made an arrangement with developer Brenwill Workshop Ltd to open-source MoltenVK under the Apache 2.0 license and as a result the library is now available on GitHub.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Valve also announced that *Dota 2* can as of February 26, 2018 run on macOS using the Vulkan API, which is based on MoltenVK.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On February 25, 2019, the Vulkan Safety Critical (SC) Working Group was announced to bring Vulkan GPU acceleration to safety critical industries.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Google's Stadia streaming cloud gaming service used Vulkan on Linux based servers with AMD GPUs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On January 15, 2020, Vulkan 1.2 was released.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Alongside the Vulkan 1.2 release, the Khronos Group posted a blog post which considered that HLSL support in Vulkan had reached "production ready" status, given the improvements in Microsoft's DXC compiler and Khronos's glslang compiler, and new features in Vulkan 1.2 which enhance HLSL support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On February 3, 2020, the Raspberry Pi Foundation announced that it was working on an open source Vulkan driver for their Raspberry Pi, a popular single board computer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On June 20, 2020, a graphics engineer revealed that he had created one after two years of work that was capable of running VkQuake3 at over 100FPS on the small computer.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On March 17, 2020, Khronos Group released the Ray Tracing extensions, based on Nvidia's proprietary extension, with some major extensions and many minor changes, which in turn was based on Nvidia's OptiX API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On November 23, 2020, these Ray Tracing extensions were finalized.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On November 24, 2020, Raspberry Pi Foundation announced that their driver for the Raspberry Pi 4 is Vulkan 1.0 conformant.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On January 25, 2022, Vulkan 1.3 was released.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On March 1, 2022, Vulkan SC 1.0 was released, bringing Vulkan graphics and compute for the safety-critical industry while being based on the Vulkan 1.2 standard.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On August 1, 2022, Raspberry Pi Foundation announced that their driver for the Raspberry Pi 4 is Vulkan 1.2 conformant.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On September 1, 2022, Mesh Shading for Vulkan was released.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] A new Vulkan Roadmap was announced on January 25, 2024.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] A new extension for decoding AV1 video was released on February 1, 2024.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Initial specifications stated that Vulkan drivers can be implemented on any hardware that supports OpenGL ES 3.1 or OpenGL 4.x and up.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] As Vulkan support requires new graphics drivers, this does not necessarily imply that every existing device that supports OpenGL ES 3.1 or OpenGL 4.x will have Vulkan drivers available.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] As of March 2023, Intel has split Vulkan driver support on Windows and on Linux.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On Windows, Skylake to Ice Lake supports up to Vulkan 1.3, with limited support after July 2022 as future updates will only cover security fixes.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Iris Xe and newer are fully supported as of March 2023.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On Linux, as of March 2023 there is incomplete Vulkan support for Haswell with it not being Vulkan 1.0 compliant.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Apart from Haswell, Ivy Bridge and Broadwell are also supported by a legacy Vulkan driver in Mesa called HASVK.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Skylake and newer being supported by a driver in Mesa called ANV.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On Windows, Vulkan 1.2 is supported from GCN 1.0 to GCN 3.0, with no further updates planned after June 2021.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On Linux there are various different Vulkan drivers with varying and overlapping hardware support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] There is the open-source Vulkan driver called AMDVLK, developed by AMD which mirrors Windows support.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] There is also the proprietary driver called AMDGPU-PRO which is not recommended to be used for most users as of March 2023.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] There is also the recommended driver called RADV in Mesa developed by Valve, Red Hat, Google and others.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] This driver as of March 2023 supports all GCN and RDNA cards.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On Windows and Linux there is the NVIDIA developed Vulkan driver which supports Vulkan 1.2 on Kepler cards with no further updates planned after September 2021.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Maxwell and newer cards support Vulkan 1.4.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] NVK, an experimental, open source Vulkan driver for Linux based on nouveau, was announced in October 2022.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] It was merged into mainline Mesa in August 2023.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] The driver is currently Vulkan 1.4 conformant on Turing and newer cards, Vulkan 1.3 conformant on Maxwell, Pascal and Volta cards and Vulkan 1.2 conformant on Kepler cards.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Most modern Android devices support Vulkan.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Android 7.0 Nougat includes optional Vulkan 1.0 support, Android 9.0 Pie includes optional Vulkan 1.1 support, and Android 10 expects (but does not require) that all non-low memory 64-bit devices support Vulkan 1.1.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Android 13 expects under the same conditions support of Vulkan 1.3.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] On Linux and some ChromeOS devices, the open-source Mesa driver provides support for Arm Mali (Midgard and Bifrost), Qualcomm Adreno, and Broadcom VideoCore VI hardware.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] As of June 2022, Apple devices do not provide native support for the Vulkan API.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan support is available via the open-source library MoltenVK, which provides a Vulkan implementation on top of the Metal graphics API provided on iOS and macOS devices, though it has some limitations in regards to certain advanced API features.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] In June 2022, version 1.3.217 of Vulkan added support for Metal objects, facilitating import and export between the two APIs.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] In December 2022, Vulkan version 1.3.236 added small fixes for the interaction with Apple Metal.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] As of August 2023, Huawei provides supports for native Vulkan NAPI with the industry standard SPIR-V shader since HarmonyOS 4.0 API 10 and extended into HarmonyOS NEXT iterative system for current HarmonyOS versions.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Microsoft supports Vulkan 1.2 (and higher) on Windows 10 and 11, with a downloadable compatibility pack.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Vulkan is not backwards compatible with OpenGL, although there are certain projects that implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan, such as Google's ANGLE and Mesa's Zink.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Nor is Vulkan compatible with other graphics APIs such as Direct3D, Metal, and Mantle.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] Platform-specific graphics APIs implemented atop of Vulkan may also be able to run on alternative platforms.
[src:mesa-graphics-stack/vulkan] For example, DXVK provides an alternative shared library intended to be used on Linux natively (without the Wine compatibility layer) to help with game porting.
